solutions.content:
There are two solutions in this post. The second approach is based on the first approach. 
The second approach supports adding new symbols or loading them in runtime without changing the code, one important aspect in code design. (e.g. S.O.L.I.D)

The main idea is to get each digit from left to right of the input `num`, convert each digit to Roman numeral(s) according to the Substraction rules and Mappings at the bottom of the post, and combine them as the final result.

For example: the mappings below are examples for [1,10).

```
1  -> I
2  -> II
3  -> III
4  -> IV (not IIII)
5  -> V
6  -> VI
7  -> VII
8  -> VIII
9  -> IX (not VIIII)
```
The mappings above are coded in the method `intToRoman` below, with "I", "V", "X" passed as arguments for the case of [1,10).
	`intToRoman(rs, num % 10, "I", "V", "X"); //get 4 in 1234`

The same principle applies to tens, hundreds, and thousands when a single digit is considered and mapped to its respective Roman symbols. 

See the mappings at the bottom of the post for tens, hundreds, and thousands.

The solution below is intuitive and easy to understand and remember, which is what matters during interviews.


```
class Solution {
	public String intToRoman(int num) {
		StringBuilder rs = new StringBuilder();
		intToRoman(rs, num / 1000, "M", "", ""); //get 1 in 1234
		intToRoman(rs, num / 100 % 10, "C", "D", "M"); //get 2 in 1234
		intToRoman(rs, num / 10 % 10, "X", "L", "C");  //get 3 in 1234
		intToRoman(rs, num % 10, "I", "V", "X"); //get 4 in 1234
		return rs.toString();
	}

 //Comments are an example of [1,10)
  private void intToRoman(StringBuilder sb, int num, String one, String five, String ten) {
		if (1 <= num) {
			if (num < 4) {
				sb.append(one.repeat(num)); //this is I, or II, or III, one could be I, X C, M depending on whether it is under tens, tens, hundreds, or thousands
			} else if (num < 5) { // num >= 4 && num < 5)
				sb.append(one).append(five); //this is IV
			} else if (num == 5) {
				sb.append(five); //this V
			} else if (num < 9) { // num > 5 && num < 9
				sb.append(five).append(one.repeat(num - 5)); //this is VI, or VII, or VIII
			} else { // num >= 9 && num < 10
				sb.append(one).append(ten); //this is IX
			}
		}
	}
}
```

