The base case is when the `root->val == sum` and the node is a leaf (ie: both `!root-left` and `!root->right` are true); if not, we keep recursing with decreased values of `sum`:

Notice that since the nodes can also have negative values, there is no way to know in advance when you have summed "too much" and thus you should stop exploring down.

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    bool hasPathSum(TreeNode* root, int sum) {
        return root && (!root->left && !root->right && root->val == sum || hasPathSum(root->left, sum - root->val) || hasPathSum(root->right, sum - root->val));
    }
};
```

