## Approach 1. recursive
---
##### Time complexity: O(n)
##### Space complexity: O(n)
```python
class Solution:
    def hasPathSum(self, root: Optiona[TreeNode], targetSum: int) -> bool:
        if root == None:
            return False

        if root.left == None and root.right == None:
            return targetSum == root.val

        return self.hasPathSum(root.left, targetSum - root.val) or self.hasPathSum(root.right, targetSum - root.val)
```
## Approach 2. iterative
---
##### Time complexity: O(n)
##### Space complexity: O(n)
```python
class Solution:
    def hasPathSum(self, root: Optional[TreeNode], targetSum: int) -> bool:
        if root == None:
            return False

        stack = [(root, targetSum - root.val)]

        while len(stack) > 0:
            node, remainder = stack.pop()

            if node.left == None and node.right == None and remainder == 0:
                return True

            if node.left != None:
                stack.append((node.left, remainder - node.left.val))

            if node.right != None:
                stack.append((node.right, remainder - node.right.val))

        return False
```
## Approach 3. Morris traversal
---
##### Time complexity: O(n)
##### Space complexity: O(1)

This solution is thanks to [ayuanx](https://leetcode.com/problems/path-sum/discuss/36435/C%2B%2B-Non-recursive-O(1)-space-solution-based-on-Morris-Traversal). The intuition behind it is that we keep track of the path sum so far while we traverse down the tree, where `m` is updated when we move the root pointer down the tree, and `n` is updated when we're setting up successor relationships / [threading the tree](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Threaded_binary_tree). When we're about to explore a different path, we subtract the current path's sum `n` from the total path sum `m`.

```python
class Solution:
    def hasPathSum(self, root: Optional[TreeNode], targetSum: int) -> bool:
        m = 0

        while root != None:
            if root.left == None:
                m += root.val
                root = root.right

                if root == None and m == targetSum:
                    return True
            else:
                prev = root.left
                n = prev.val

                while prev.right != None and prev.right != root:
                    prev = prev.right
                    n += prev.val

                if prev.right == None:
                    m += root.val
                    prev.right = root

                    if prev.left == None and m + n == targetSum:
                        return True

                    root = root.left
                else:
                    prev.right = None
                    root = root.right
                    m -= n

        return False
```

