solutions.content:
> **I. Brute-force:** try every balloon on by one, then solve the sub problem recursively.
>
```python
    class Solution:
        def maxCoins(self, nums) -> int:
            k, dp = "1"*len(nums), {}
            nis = [(i,c) for i, c in enumerate(nums)]

            def _max(sub_nis, k, dp):
                if not sub_nis:
                    return 0
                if k in dp:
                    return dp[k]
                x = 0
                for i in range(len(sub_nis)):
                    left, it, right = _coin(sub_nis, i-1), _coin(sub_nis, i), _coin(sub_nis, i+1)
                    sub = sub_nis[:i] + sub_nis[i+1:]
                    x = max(x, left[1]*it[1]*right[1]+_max(sub, k[:it[0]]+"0"+k[it[0]+1:], dp))
                dp[k] = x
                return x

            def _coin(nis, i):
                if i < 0 or i >= len(nis):
                    return (-1, 1)
                return nis[i]

            x = _max(nis, k, dp)
            return x
```
>
> recursive expresion of this brutal idea is:  

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/pizzacrystal/image_1569314831.png)

> easy to figure out its time complexity is $O(n!)$, hereby it no doubt exceeds time limitation.  

> **II. Optimized Brute-force:** omits array slices by delaying calculation until getting valid $X_{right}$.
>
```python
    class Solution:
        def maxCoins(self, nums) -> int:
            if not nums:
                return 0
            k, dp = "1"*len(nums), {}

            def _burst(nums, k, dp):
                if k in dp:
                    return dp[k]
                l2left, left, _max, _len, j = None, 1, 0, len(nums), -1
                for i in range(_len):
                    if k[i] == '0':
                        continue
                    if l2left is not None:
                        _max = max(_max, l2left*left*nums[i]+_burst(nums, k[:j]+"0"+k[j+1:], dp))
                    l2left, left, j = left, nums[i], i
                else:
                    if j != -1:
                        _max = max(_max, l2left*left+_burst(nums, k[:j]+"0"+k[j+1:], dp))
                dp[k] = _max
                return _max

            x = _burst(nums, k, dp)
            return x
```
>
> time complexity is still $O(n!)$, though this implementation has higher performance.  

> **III. DP (top down):** thinking of selecting the first balloon is inevitably TLE, which prompts us to address it in another way -- consider the case of picking the last one. if we knew $X$ should be picked in the end, we get the transition equation as below:  

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/pizzacrystal/image_1569314893.png)

> apparently, we need to examine every $X$ in $A$, but it is remarkably faster than brute-force method because of "devide and conquer". As for memoization, we could use a 2-D array $dp[i][j]$ to cache results of left and right sub arrays. Here is the implementation:  
>
```python
    class Solution:
        def maxCoins(self, nums) -> int:
            if not nums:
                return 0
            _len = len(nums)
            dp = [[-1]*_len for _ in range(_len)]

            def _burst(left, right, b, e):
                if e < b:
                    return 0
                if dp[b][e] != -1:
                    return dp[b][e]
                _max = 0
                if b == e:
                    dp[b][e] = left * nums[b] * right
                else:
                    for i in range(b, e+1):
                        last = left * nums[i] * right
                        lhalf = _burst(left, nums[i], b, i-1)
                        rhalf = _burst(nums[i], right, i+1, e)
                        _max = max(_max, last+lhalf+rhalf)
                    dp[b][e] = _max
                return dp[b][e]

            return _burst(1, 1, 0, _len-1)
```
>
> recursion tree is in need to analyse time complexity, omitted here.  

> **IV. DP (bottom up):** By translating recursion cycles to for-loops, we get the final solution.
>
```python
    class Solution:
        def maxCoins(self, nums) -> int:
            if not nums:
                return 0
            nums = [1] + nums + [1]
            _len = len(nums)
            dp = [[0]*_len for _ in range(_len)]

            for l in range(1, _len+1):
                for i in range(1, _len-l):
                    j = i + l - 1
                    for k in range(i, j+1):
                        dp[i][j] = max(dp[i][j], nums[i-1]*nums[k]*nums[j+1]+dp[i][k-1]+dp[k+1][j])
            return dp[1][_len-2]
```
>
> the inner loop calculates coins of specific array, while the outer two loops examine all sub arrays that are of length $1$ to length $n$, thereby we get correct result finally. Time complexity is $O(n^3)$, which is overwhelming compared to $O(n!)$.

