solutions.content:
**UPDATE**:
* LC has recently uploaded the solution to this problem which is of top quality. This itself is enough to solve this problem now.
* Teaches:
 \xA0  * the pattern of how a subsequent problem can be turned  into subarray problem.
 \xA0 * time complexity of subsequence(aka subsets) is always O(2^N) and subarray is always O(N\xB2).
 \xA0 * Here, O(2^N) states in the first approach are the the non-overlapped subproblems in time complexity representation. Actual value/steps would be N!. If overlapped subproblems are also considered, then time complexity would be O(N^N). 
 \xA0 * a combo of: DP + Divide Conquer + Thinking Backwards

**ORIGINAL**:
**Concept**:
* Naive approach: is plain recursion of O(n!)
* Optimal approach: DP in O(n\xB3)
 \xA0 * Approach the problem as **"solve for array from i to j"** and cache (i,j) value.
 \xA0 * **Pick the last cadidate**. This is what males the concept tricky since till now all DP problems had the pattern of pick first candidate. Where this is something like Post Order Traversal concept. Why last? Read below.
 \xA0 * **Solve left and right sub problems** recursively. (To solve these left and right sub problems, they should be independent, which wouldn't have been the case if we had picked first candidate above. Reason: due to subarray order instead of subsequence order as in [Connect sticks](https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-cost-to-connect-sticks) )
 \xA0 * What are the neighbours of `i` (or any element of the state (state = subarray defined by start and end) ): start - 1 and end + 1 (see image in approach's link)
 * Incorrect approach: Greedy
One would first think greedily like [Connect sticks](https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-cost-to-connect-sticks). But Burst Balloons has subarray format (i - 1, i, i + 1) and not subsequence format (where sort and then pick greedily was possible)

**Approach**: [Click here](https://leetcode.com/problems/burst-balloons/discuss/892552/For-those-who-are-not-able-to-understand-any-solution-WITH-DIAGRAM?page=2)

**Similar problems**:
* This is a variation of classic problem of Matrix Chain Multiplication from the book CLRS.
* https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-cost-to-connect-sticks
* https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-cost-to-merge-stones 
* https://leetcode.com/problems/remove-boxes
* https://leetcode.com/problems/strange-printer
* I think the same approach can be used for the problem https://leetcode.com/problems/24-game

**Code**: 
```
class Solution {
    public int maxCoins(int[] nums) {
        int n = nums.length;
        return f(nums, n, 0, n - 1, new int[n][n]);
    }

    private int f(int[]nums, int n, int start, int end, int[][] cache){
        // base
        if (start > end) return 0;
        // cache out
        if (cache[start][end] > 0) return cache[start][end];

        // recurse
        int max = 0;
        for (int i = start; i <= end; i++){
            int sum = 0;
            sum += f(nums, n, start, i - 1, cache);
            sum += f(nums, n, i + 1, end, cache);

            int prevNum = start == 0 ? 1 : nums[start - 1];
            int nextNum = end == n - 1 ? 1 : nums[end + 1];
            sum += prevNum * nums[i] * nextNum;

            max = Math.max(max, sum);
        }

        // cache in
        cache[start][end] = max;

        // return 
        return max;
    }
}
```

